    </div>
    <div class="w-full lg:w-7/12 lg:px-8">
      <div class="mb-10">
        <h2 class="mb-4 font-serif text-3xl font-bold text-center uppercase sm:text-left sm:text-4xl text-oak">
          Common Tactics
        </h2>
        <hr class="w-4/5 mx-auto border-2 sm:w-full lg:w-4/5 border-oak sm:mx-0">
      </div>
      <div class="mb-8 text-lg text-center sm:text-left tactic-info-container">
        <div class="space-y-4 active-tactic-text" data-tactic="passedPawn">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">passed pawn</span> is a pawn that has no opposing pawns blocking its path to
            promotion. This makes it a powerful asset in the endgame, as it can advance to the eighth rank and promote
            without obstruction.
          </p>
          <p>
            A passed pawn is most effective when supported by other pieces, as it can create multiple threats and
            distract the opponent's forces.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4" data-tactic="forks">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">fork</span> is a tactic which involves attacking two undefended or higher valued
            pieces at the same time, forcing the opponent to make a tough decision.
          </p>
          <p>
            Pawns can fork pieces by advancing to a square where they attack two or more pieces simultaneously.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4" data-tactic="pawnPyramid">
          <p>
            A <span class="font-bold">pawn pyramid</span> is a formation where pawns are stacked on top of each other
            to create a strong defensive structure. This setup can protect the pawns and control key squares on the
            board.
          </p>
          <p>
            By maintaining this structure, players can create a solid foundation for their pieces and limit the
            opponent's options.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap justify-center gap-2 sm:justify-start tactics">
